Bakala's tenant: heats up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, old and old, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnet" Zdeÿek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-storey lease contracts: his, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving his sentence.
All three of them just caught up in the rental liberalisation.
Instead of 3,500 Czech kroner per month, the child will pay from next year 4100 kroner for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, on which he has full powers.
"But I signed it," explains half angry, half resigned.
BytyOKD.cz civil association, which described new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign new contracts and wait until 7 December, when they will publish a guide informing them of how to proceed in these cases.
But, before this, man only makes an ademan.
"Everything he says," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major testing laboratory for liberalization.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the floors that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
That's why Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
RPG's mining waiting room is one of the four of Ostrava's and, on Tuesday at nine o'clock, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to take number.
"Rental 2011", can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper comes out of the machine with a number.
Almost no time to read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Soon after, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd of the room is not here for the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as old times: settlement requests, insurance issues and similar issues.
Letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the boxes of tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers you in the cards an increase in rent from 15 to 38%.
On November 18 a special window is opened in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting," responds, after briefly doubting, the workers who find themselves in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and the old floors for Bakala miners are the most delicate topics in the area.
Before the elections, the Vice-President of Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, treated them loud and clear, and now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"I didn't even get changed by the damn bathroom dish," the man mentioned in the introduction was evicted.
According to workers, at the moment they come more than retired to check if they get a discount on the rent if they sign in time, as promised by RPG's special offer.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before 15 December will also receive half of the discount on the February rental.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rent in 2011 about forty or fifty people," estimates the employee of the window.
In the meantime, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach agreement on the rent, an independent judge will have to settle the matter.
"It's not a threat, it's information about the only possible and complete way of proceeding according to the law," RPG warns on his pages.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of RPG Byty's employees and a man on the street in front of the customer service centre gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court," he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek warns you in the media not to sign, so maybe people wait," he says.
The rental regulation will cease to exist in the majority of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not cover even the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the owners, the main reason to increase the rent.
While during the five years that passed between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen that hangs from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of the properties of RPG."
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech kronor per square metre per month," is indicated on the screen.
Just increase by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 kroner per square metre," says RPG.
On 2,600 floors, the rental will remain invariable next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalisation will not affect rents at any rate, but will climb from four to eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rental rise (see chart) back on the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the lease raise agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides in his interior a small nursery with all the same to such installations: walls of colors, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design's employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, of which numerous well-known buildings came out of Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
In the company they work about 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, day care is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers within the framework of its social program.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of the children.
Miniguardy was an idea of Arch's own employees.Designu and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guardy is financed through the European Social Fund under the operational programme for human resources and employment, as well as the Czech state budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a total of more than 2.8 million Czech kroner) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When you exhaust the funding (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-guardry running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the application for funding contributed the company Economy Rating.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff; moreover, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nursery currently accommodates children without a limit of age, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "ministry", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible in order to adapt to the needs of the parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the enterprise.
Although it is a matter of individual education and care, the contents of the mini-care programme are comparable to the regular pre-school education programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of collecting late school children when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design stands among the companies sign that they offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that recalls the scales and the ubiquitous lines gently curved, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with oniric lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
By paying more attention, there is a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is lit so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twisting of forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signboards.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gracia, emerged from the remodeling of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of making a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He collaborated in the design of the architect Josep María Jujol.
In fact, in its plans of the project appeared ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Güell de Gaudí park, where other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows, began to call it "the house of the bostizos".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating period with ventilating vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange his inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply at all with the rules of construction of the moment and was not allowed to influence them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so impacted with the result that it requested that it be corrected.
He was disturbed, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: just fifteen days after the City Council's request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two upper floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor there was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform were to break all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only gained a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with both colors brings the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and charged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the gutter, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16,50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of entry of other Gaudí buildings into the city.
