More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device has the approximate size of a matchbox, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička case and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that it is not about spying, but about another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy," considers Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's purse without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In their view, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to take him, he will simply throw him away.
"Even younger children show great creativity in intentionally losing certain things if they want to prevent them from being controlled."
"Before, parents trusted the mobiles enormously, but they could be switched off as easily as the tracking device," says Bočková.
In your opinion, it is questionable whether in the event of an attack such a device is really useful.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the author will almost always check whether the child has any kind of electronic device that can reveal his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is expanding, it will also look for them, since their sale will certainly be carried out with a lot of publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers follow-up services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is destroyed immediately, its presence can help.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a given period."
"If you suffer damage, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person concerned."
"The most expensive devices include a tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
In your opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smart mobile phones with navigation, where only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that for the time being they are devices with a size similar to a box of matches or smaller mobile phones.
