Prosecutors will not press charges against Senator Ensign
Senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday that the prosecutors of the Department of Justice have forgiven Senator John Ensign for the criminal charges that arose from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure work through lobbying for the wife's husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal about his affair had national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said he felt "certainly happy" for the decision, which came after an investigation of a whole year.
The senator could still face a disciplinary action by the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said that the Department of Justice had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of his investigation and that he has no plan to press charges against him on this issue."
The Department of Justice did not want to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there seemed to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign might have confabulated to violate a federal criminal lobby ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents that were first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to gain gain gainful work through lobbying, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as treasurer of an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find Mr. Hampton's work and counseled on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
Since Hampton had recently been an Ensign assistant, he was excluded under the law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethical experts said that the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared in disagreement with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it seemed to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the door-revolving status," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While the officials of the Department of Justice refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed cautious in accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year's decision to abandon prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, in the midst of charges of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards," said Melanie Sloan, Executive Director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that laws do not apply to them," he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's main lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor from the Department of Justice on Monday and another phone call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to press charges against his client.
Ensign's defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in trying to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave the prosecutors.
"I don't feel comfortable getting into details about my discussions with the Department of Justice, I can only say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation into a complaint separated by the ethics group, claiming that a payment of $96,000 from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal electoral law.
The electoral commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was nothing more than a gift.
NV Energy is an important Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got work through lobbying thanks to Ensign's help to Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him that he was "masking" the Ministry of the Interior on a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended lunch with Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and called the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the affair first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he planned to apply for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign's spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, he said that the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the Department of Justice's example and complete its investigation.
"Senator Ensign has a desire to continue his difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada," he said.
