The jurors weren't kidnapped.
But their arguments on the effect of intense process coverage can attract most of the interest.
They observed in a refusal to the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media were continually throwing firewood at the emotion of the case.
"The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the court," the lawyers wrote, "was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps in the whole state."
Your attention to Tweeter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that the complaint about the fact that the immediate news was more important than the reports delivered more slowly, was a ludicrous vision that would make the court's policy on coverage control weak in future processes.
But some lawyers said that the courts of appeal were often attracted to the arguments on the adaptation required in the courts due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pressing for that claim.
In their writing, they referred to the 1966 decision of the Supreme Court, which revoked Dr. Sheppard's conviction due to the coverage of the trial, and made it clear that they would require new media to require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the Sheppard vs. Maxwell case of the 21st century."
Can civilism build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, this week has triggered a bit of civicism in Washington.
Is it a sign of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to party combat in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not yield any progress on the major issues to be dealt with during the outgoing session.
But from what they all say, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the President's deficit committee was equally civilised, despite the political differences that still exist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a trial period, testing each other to identify signs of co-operativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent evaluations of the meeting by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and are deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"They're inevitable after the election.
The elections awaken partisan passions, which then become extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, the Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are won at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make believe that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, together with the ratification of the new START nuclear disarmament pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanism when the new 112nd Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very probable and even inevitable that a period of disagreement should begin.
"After the things to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to fulfill their promises to cut state spending and nullify the new health law.
These lines of support are already clearly observed in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, including the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and the retirement age, and the cut in expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected to the panel, suggesting that there is, at least at present, little basis or desire for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks he's losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partyism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties view 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked American document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "chleptocracy", and leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money that directly collects the Kremlin, according to the U.S. Embassy in Russia in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service handle huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of life in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called "vertical authority," takes its share as money rises on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns an important construction company, have systematically denied the accusations of corruption over the years, and he has won several lawsuits for libel on such accusations.
In September, when on a Russian television channel he was asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt, he said, "It's crazy, it's a patsy, it's a mess."
According to the polls, the Russians believe overwhelmingly that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy's report, and it is unheard of that it is the diplomats of a foreign country who do so.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government with crime have led some to call it 'disfunctional', and to affirm that the government functions more as a cleptocracy than as a government," the note says.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a term of the criminal world and mafia that literally means "text" or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor's office, as well as all sectors of the bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"The analysts identify a three-tier structure in Moscow's criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the highest."
"SFS, MVD and militia are on the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas, because the city does not provide some services."
The report states that the SFS collects money from larger companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report said, "explained that Moscow's business owners understand that it is best to protect MVD and SFS (instead of organized crime groups) because they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law."
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority."
The note notes that while money collection is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not quickly pay find their businesses closed for one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has achieved little progress.
The embassy note reports about men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of India's Moscow expert group, in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy."
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia."
Without politics, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
At the national level, India estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey on global perceptions of corruption conducted by the NGO Transparency International, the country was ranked 154 (countries are ranked at least as corrupt).
The revelation of the U.S. Embassy note, which did not happen until late in Moscow's evening, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow's weaknesses, could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that WikiLeaks documents could be lies and he reacted furiously by a revelation claiming that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country," he said.
"But to be honest with you, we do not suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would be done in such an immoral way."
The veterans of the Red Jemers forced to face the past
In a concrete classroom weakly lit, with stained and peeled walls, the director of the Anlong Veng Secondary School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Ta Mok Red Jemers.
"Here everyone loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and cared about his people," said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the Carnicero" for his brutality during the government of the Red Jemeres, the commander remains popular in this remote former fortress of the Red Jemeres in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Jemers surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to face publicly those who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Red Jemeres to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a United Nations and Cambodia mixed court issued the first sentence of a former member of the Red Jemeres, sentencing the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Red Jemeres of Anlong Veng, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among former Red Jemeres, but they can't do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"For them, life under the Red Jemers was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"This is generating divisions within families."
During the government of the Cambodian Red Jemeres, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrowed the government led by Pol Pot, the remains of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
Like Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of fighters from the Red Jemers began to defect to the government, culminating in Ieng Sary's 1996 returns and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan's 1998 returns.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of its benefactors, the oldest fighters of the Red Jemeres fell into absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few Red Jemer elite officials retained their local administrative positions in exchange for laying down their weapons, the shallow soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have gained few benefits after surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the utopian agricultural ideology of the regime."
"They were raised without any concept to do business."
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Red Jemeres when he was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Red Jemers was fine," he said.
"Ta Mok fed everyone."
"But now life is hard because we have to self-supply."
The current Court of the Red Jemers has also caused concerns here.
Early next year, the court is expected to start prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former minister of the Red Jemeres.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the main leaders and those with greater responsibility for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases in addition to those four.
This did not help much to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
The recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the government of the Red Jemeres in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced labourers were thought to have died.
During a recent noisy afternoon, Im Chaem returned to work in the fields at his home on wooden pilots on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the dry pasture, Im Chaem refused to speak of his past in the Red Jemeres.
She stated that if the court summoned her, she would not appear.
"Camboya is at peace and stable," he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who deserted the Red Jemers in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
"Camboya must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is just what Cambodia must do to move forward, Chhang Youk said, from the documentation centre.
"Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to rejoin the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our obligation to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The center produced the first textbook approved by the government on the Red Jemeres, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the secondary school history textbook of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Red Jemeres.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know few details about the Red Jemeres, despite the city's connection to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court," he said.
"They have suspicions because they are not sure how many people will sue the court."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to produce an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Red Jemers retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a road with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of the black soot covered by an oxidized roof of leaf.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a lot of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone salesman on the edge of the road, said he didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray to him," he said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day he decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot's last break, where he would leave a handful of mature bananas hoping to have good luck.
Belarus agrees to renounce its reserve of uranium qualified for armaments
In a surprising victory for President Obama's campaign to protect nuclear material around the world, the Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will renounce its highly enriched uranium reserve, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement issued after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov, on the margins of a security summit.
For years, the U.S. government had been trying to persuade Belarus to renounce its highly enriched uranium and it seemed that they had reached a point without return last spring.
But U.S. officials told the Washington Post that a couple of operations were conducted classified with Belarus in the last two months, to remove 84.82 kg of qualified uranium for weaponry from a Belarusian investigation facility.
This paved the way for Wednesday's agreement to remove the rest of the material, approximately 227 kg, according to one official, who spoke from anonymity due to the confidentiality of the subject.
The agreement seemed to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And apparently it was a good achievement to ensure the invitation of the former Soviet Republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I really felt fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit."
"This shows that this process is working," said Ken Luongo, president of the Global Security Society, a group that promotes nuclear safety.
Clinton said the agreement is "a very significant and important step" given by Belarus.
In April 2009, Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide in the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries to get rid of all its highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of Obama's Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had declared that the nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have conserved highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what is basically uranium qualified for armaments) and low enriched uranium," Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material... we're not going to make dirty bombs, and we're not going to sell them to anyone."
"We use it for research purposes, that's all."
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials stated that the first task of withdrawing uranium from Belarus in October was particularly complicated, as the material had been slightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded on a special train that traveled more than 2,000 km to a Russian facility for storage and disposal.
According to the officials, the second operation ended on Monday and was made by plane.
The U.S. government spent $13 million on tasks, and most of the money was used to provide Belarus with low-enrichment uranium research, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an Energy Department official working on Global Threat Reduction, said that "this was coordinated and orchestrated with great care to strengthen confidence" that led to the agreement signed by Clinton.
