Sport and law fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in front of Ajax prove ingenious but not willing to escape a sanction.
The alleged expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match held on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether such behavior is anti-sportive and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time in taking away faults to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of its group, both players will carry out the regulatory sanction the next game of the Liguilla, against the Auxerre, and will be able to pass cards clean to the next stage.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two parties, and with different economic amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case reported is that it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and who in past times has fined his players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether such behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e., whether such actions are fraud of law; for they are indeed actions that are respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question goes on to examine the type of damage to the sporting spirit.
One of the goods that understands the sport spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in jeopardy, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that is referred to with the clean game is to prevent the equipment of the offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposite equipment, which also did not happen.
However, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it did not conform to what we normally characterized as a trap or a law fraud, because its violation of the rules was not made hidden to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely its action tried to be the most obvious so as to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is what kind of advantage offenders gain from the intentional misdemeanours examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not placed at a disadvantage or profit in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will begin the next phase of the League of Champions without cards that may threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminateness, as the team can be eliminated from the first of the changes, and in addition with this performance the players play a penalty game and pass to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards is produced with a less than in the first cycle.
So, if you're going through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not run counter to the sport spirit, of which it is a part to make strategic decisions that favor to make the most of what the rules allow.
In the event that we are concerned, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without drawing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and lawlessness is diffuse, on this occasion I believe it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was a matter of two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them was carried out.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
