EU changes rules to get visa
People should go to Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time will be lower.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff shall take the biometric information of the applicant, which shall be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with a request (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
People wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Likewise, those applying for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletins/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
