A Global Plan to Refurbish Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) in a quantity that corresponds to almost one third of the additional decrease to be carried out to stabilize the climate of the planet by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major specific projects that the United Nations hopes will be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, are replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting accounts for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of emissions from the planetary fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should be further reduced to stabilize by 2020 the increase in temperatures by two degrees centigrade in order to avoid uncontrolled.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the Philips manufacturer this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with reostats and emit very little heat.
Above all, they contain no mercury.
Various specialists have expressed their reservations regarding fluocompact light bulbs, since they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluocompact bulbs, but coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that melts with incandescent bulbs.
Only in the United States do these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save billion dollars a year on electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants costing 2.5 billion.
