Avenger hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous at the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (independent of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving Cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or don't know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who engage in occultism not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they have already learned.
This is Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or he has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, libération editor), who only considers what he can recognize true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the American Embassy of Rome to the State Department was the same information published by Newsweek the previous week.
Then why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since the heads of States can call on the telephone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of limited representation exercises, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who sees research films knows perfectly well, we just seem to know that we don't know it because of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "Verdugos".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Previously, in Orwell's time, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as is now the case, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer hold its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from it.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put on the network any confidential information, since it would be like publishing it on a sign on the street.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, we cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the telephone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has flown and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is a science fiction thing and, therefore, a new one, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at the very least, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
This information is then stored in a single copy in locked drawers: after all, the attempt to spy on Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with cables (telephones).
The video tapes (analogues) had allowed cinema researchers to study a film step by step, advancing and retreating, discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (digital) only allow moving or going back from chapter to chapter, i.e. to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can travel from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the trips it carries, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that communication policy and techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
Previously, the press was trying to understand what was being done secretly in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's headlines in its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to consider whether the rapidly unlocked funding promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed themselves to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation proved appreciable and was appreciated for what was really worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion, placing it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, everyone chooses the most suitable reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken the year 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added in three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years ' expenditure or the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the sharing of donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (frequently, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is false to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... As a lot, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million); consult the EU document to see it in its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is doing a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, he gets the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a short-term, short-term one in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could make progress in the discussions on the stakes at stake in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional nature" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive in relation to this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional nature" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning on pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old ingests 81 different chemicals on a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the Generations Futures association (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with", acquired in supermarkets of Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that usually consume a child of about ten years at four meals and one snack per day.
These meals taken as a model, which respect official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day), as well as candy, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
"Although in virtually all cases the legal limits for each individual chemical are not exceeded, our study clearly shows that exposure of consumers to potentially carcinogenic pollutants and/or PE is of concern," says the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea contain by themselves more than a dozen possible cancer residues and three considered safe cancers, as well as about twenty residues that may harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as intended for school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a prohibited fungicide in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, where the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the Russian steak, canned tuna and even the bread bar or gum were fitted with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk that these "pollutant cocktails" generate to the consumer is "probably underestimated," says the study.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "against the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
